## Multicenter clinical trial on sentinel lymph node biopsy using superparamagnetic iron oxide nanoparticles and a novel handheld magnetic probe

## Abstract

Background: Sentinel lymph node biopsy is a standard staging procedure for early axillary lymph node /uni2010 negative breast cancer. As an alternative to the currently used radioactive tracers for sentinel lymph node (SLN) detection during the surgical procedure, a number of studies have shown promising results using superparamagnetic iron oxide (SPIO) nanoparticles. Here, we developed a new handheld, cordless, and lightweight magnetic probe for SPIO detection.

Methods: Resovist (SPIO nanoparticles) were detected by the newly developed handheld probe, and the SLN detection rate was compared to that of the standard radioisotope (RI) method using radioactive colloids ( 99m Tc) and a blue dye (indigo carmine). This was a multicenter prospective clinical trial that included 220 patients with breast cancer scheduled for sentinel node biopsy after a clinical diagnosis of negative axillary lymph node from three facilities in Japan.

Results: Of the 210 patients analyzed, SLN was detected in 94.8% (199/210 cases, 90% confidence interval [CI]) with our magnetic method and in 98.1% (206/210 cases, 90% CI) with the RI method. The magnetic method exceeded the threshold identification rate of 90%.

Conclusion: This was the first clinical study to use a novel handheld magnetometer to detect SLN, which we demonstrate to be not inferior to the RI method.

## 1 | INTRODUCTION

Sentinel lymph node (SLN) biopsy (SLNB) was progressively introduced in the 1990s 1 and is now used as a standard staging procedure for early axillary lymph node /uni2010 negative breast cancer. 2 In Japan, SLNB was approved for insurance coverage in 2009. 3 The false /uni2010 negative rate of the SLNB method, according to a meta /uni2010 analysis in 9220 patients, has been reported to be only 7.3%. 4 If the SLN is positive, then axillary lymph node dissection (ALND) is recommended; however, if it is negative, then the ALND can be omitted. 5 This minimally invasive approach is associated with lower morbidity than complete lymph node removal through the conventional ALND. 6-8

Currently, SLNB is performed using a radioactive tracer alone, or in combination with blue dye. The reported detection rate is up to 97%. 9,10 However, there are health concerns associated with both methods. There is a risk of radiation exposure to patients and health care personnel as well as a dependency on the radioactive tracer for the radioactive method, and risk of allergic reactions to the blue dye. Moreover, the blue dye can be obscured in the surgical field and frequently leaves a blue stain on the skin that can take months to fade. The use of a radiotracer is limited to facilities that count with a nuclear medicine unit. Complicated legislation and restrictions regulate the handling and disposal of radioactive material. Therefore, the aforementioned drawbacks have motivated research for novel techniques. 2

One of the possible approaches to replace the method based on a radioactive tracer is the use of magnetic nanoparticles with a magnetic probe detection system, which has been compared in various clinical studies that have shown promising results. 11-14 A meta /uni2010 analysis of SLNB clinical trials using the magnetic detection system demonstrated that the SLN identification rate was not inferior to that of simultaneous administration of radioactive colloids +/ -dye (conventional method vs magnetic method: 96.8% vs 97.1%). 15 In Europe, Sienna+ has obtained CE mark approval as magnetic nanoparticles, while Sentimag has obtained CE mark approval as a magnetic probe. The use of a magnetic detection system will remove the restrictions in terms of facilities managing radioactive tracers, as well as eliminate radioactive exposure.

In Japan, the Sienna+ magnetic tracer is not available; therefore, other tracers must be evaluated. Resovist, a superparamagnetic iron oxide (SPIO) coated with carboxydextran, was originally developed as a tracer for contrast /uni2010 enhanced magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the liver.

A new original magnetic probe that differs from the Sentimag for intraoperative identification of magnetic nanoparticles in SLNs has been developed. This probe uses a static magnetic field from a permanent magnet, making it compact and easy to use. 16

Shiozawa et al 17 performed SLN biopsies for breast cancer using Resovist and a prototype of the new magnetic probe, and they demonstrated a 77% detection rate. The prototype of the new magnetic probe was further improved and evaluated in 6 patients with breast cancer, which yielded promising results. 16 We have used

the handheld magnetic probe prototype developed previously, but it is now cordless, weighs only 108 g, and is very compact and easy to use. Here, we present the results of a multicenter clinical study that evaluated the use of the Resovist magnetic particles and the newly developed handheld magnetic probe for SLNB, and we compared the detection rate of this method to the standard SLNB method (radioactive tracer 99m Tc and a blue dye).

## 2 | METHODS

## 2.1 | Clinical design and patient recruitment

A prospective multicenter study (registered as UMIN31240) was conducted in three facilities in Japan: Showa University, Showa University Fujigaoka Hospital, and Nippon Medical School. The study was approved by the local ethics committees at the facilities, and written informed consent was obtained from all patients. All procedures performed in studies involving human participants were in accordance with the ethical standards of the institutional and/or national research committee per the 1964 Helsinki declaration and its later amendments or comparable ethical standards.

From June 2016 to March 2018, 220 patients with breast cancer were recruited in the aforementioned facilities. The eligibility criteria were as follows: adult female patients older than 20 years of age who were diagnosed with breast cancer and were scheduled for sentinel node biopsy after a diagnosis of clinically node /uni2010 negative breast cancer. The exclusion criteria were as follows: intolerance or hypersensitivity to iron compounds or carboxydextran, pregnancy or lactation, having a pacemaker or other ferrous metal /uni2010 containing devices in the chest wall, breast implant insertion, liver failure, and renal failure (creatinine ≥ 1.1, AST ≥ 50, ALT ≥ 40, T /uni2010 bil ≥ 1.5).

## 2.2 | Magnetic tracer and probe

The magnetic tracer and magnetic probe were used as the nonradioactive detection system to magnetically mark and locate lymph nodes before their surgical removal and subsequent analysis. We used Ferucarbotran (Resovist; Kyowa CritiCare Co, Ltd, Kanagawa, Japan) as the magnetic tracer. Resovist was originally developed for contrast /uni2010 enhanced MRI of the liver as a magnetic tracer, and it consists of nanoparticles of a SPIO coated with carboxydextran. The injected material contains 540 mg/mL of ferucarbotran (27.9 of mg/mL of iron), consisting of an oxygen atom and iron /uni2010 covered carboxydextran as the hydroxyl group. The average hydrodynamic diameter of the particle was about 57 nm.

The magnetic probe for detection was developed at the School of Engineering at the University of Tokyo. The design of the detector is shown in Figure 1.

The magnetic probe used in this study has been miniaturized to enable the entire magnetic probe, including the drive circuit, to be held in one hand, and it has been improved to enable detection of minute amounts of iron. The probe head consists of a permanent magnet for the generation of static magnetic fields and a Hall /uni2010 effect

## 2.3 | Surgery procedure

Both the radioactive colloids ( 99m Tc) and Resovist were administered into the areolar subcutaneous tissue up to 24 hours before the surgery. Resovist was administered as 1 mL of stock solution, the injected material contained ferucarbotran 540 mg/mL (27.9 mg/mL of iron), consisting of an oxygen atom and iron /uni2010 covered carboxydextran as the hydroxyl group. The Tchne Phytate Kit (2.9 mg of phytate acid, 2 /uni2010 8mL of 99m Tc, and 111 MBq of 99m Tc) was used for the administration of 99m Tc.

The surgery was performed under general anesthesia. First, blue dye (indigo carmine 2 mL) was injected subcutaneously. Afterward we looked for the SLN by the magnetic probe method and then by the standard radioisotope (RI) method. When Tc accumulation was found with the RI probe in SLNs detected with the magnetic method, it was determined that the nodes could be detected with both methods. Lymph nodes that were found only with the supplemental

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

RI method were determined to be nodes that could not be identified with the magnetic method. Lymph nodes that were not identified with either method were excluded from the study.

## 2.4 | End points

The primary endpoint of the study was the proportion of successful detection of SLN (identification rate per patient) by the magnetic method (Resovist and the handheld magnetometer) compared with the RI method. The secondary endpoint was the concordance of detection between the magnetic and RI methods and the evaluation of side effects directly after the surgical procedure. The evaluation of long /uni2010 term side effects such as skin pigmentation will be performed on outpatient basis and is not included in this study.

## 2.5 | Statistical analysis

We used the Clopper /uni2010 Pearson method to calculate the statistical threshold for the detection rate to accept noninferiority of the magnetic method as compared to the RI method. If we assume that the detection rate of the RI method is 97%, then the noninferiority threshold is 90%, meaning that any results above 90% will be viewed as noninferior to the RI method. Over 180 cases were needed to prove noninferiority of the magnetic method, based on an expected SLN identification rate of over 90% (an expected threshold) with higher than 80% power (one side α = .05). For statistical analysis, SPSS Statistics version 23.0 (IBM Japan, Ltd, Tokyo, Japan) was used.

## 3 | RESULTS

## 3.1 | Patient characteristics

Among the 220 patients enrolled in the study, statistical analysis was performed on 210 patients. Six patients withdrew after the beginning of the study, and four were excluded due to intraoperative equipment failure (no liquid crystal display or battery shortage). The breast cancer tumors were diagnosed by core /uni2010 needle biopsy or vacuum /uni2010 assisted core biopsy. The median age was 57 years (range, 33 /uni2010 94 years). The concordance between the magnetic and RI methods was 96.1% (198/206; Table 2). The clinical characteristics of the patients where SLNs were not identified with either methods are presented in Table S1.

The magnetic method with a 94.8% detection rate exceeded the threshold identification rate of 90%, and thus we concluded that SLNB using the magnetic method is noninferior to the RI method.

The side effects that were observed with the magnetic method were mainly skin pigmentation and residual iron in the breasts. A skin tattoo remained in 22 patients 1 month after the surgical procedure.

## 4 | DISCUSSION

The noninferiority of SLNB using a magnetic substance and a magnetic probe has been verified in the French Sentimag, 13 Nordic Sentimag trial, 11 Sentimag Multicenter Trial, 14 and Central /uni2010 European Sentimag trial, 12 as well as other studies. 18,19 In those studies, patients received injections of both SPIO and 99m Tc, with or without blue dye. To address the concern of whether the results can be influenced by the presence of both tracers, a subsequent clinical trial evaluated the use of SPIO alone and compared it with 99m Tc; the results showed that the detection rates were comparable for both methods. 20

Here, we present a SLNB clinical trial using Resovist, the only magnetic substance particle that can be currently used in Japan, and a miniature probe that we newly developed. This study demonstrated that this method was not inferior to the conventional RI method. We aim to further improve this method to be comparable to the Sentimag method.

Establishing magnetic methods in Japan will enable SLNB to be reliably implemented in facilities without a radiation /uni2010 controlled area (currently in approximately 30% of facilities). Moreover, in Japan, the supply of radioactive isotopes is dependent on imports, and therefore is unreliable due to the weather and conditions at the supply source. 21 Furthermore, magnetic methods are easier and safer, and those can replace the RI method in the future, even in facilities with radiation /uni2010 controlled areas. The price for both methods is comparable, 20 and there is no dependence on radioactive isotope supply nor a need for radiation /uni2010 controlled areas and imaging facilities with the

magnetic method. More accurate SLNB will lead to a reduction in the number of patients waiting for surgery (the wait time in Japan is around 1 /uni2010 3 months), 22 further reducing health care costs. Although our main focus was to develop a method that can be routinely implemented in Japan, we plan to further expand our techniques to other countries. We have already obtained a CE mark for a medical device registration on the EU market (93/42/EEC), and we plan to apply for the marketing authorization for the US.

The Sentimag system uses an electromagnet coil and requires a large power supply. 16 On the other hand, our handheld magnetometer has a permanent magnet and a Hall magnetic sensor. We were able to merge the probe body and the driving circuit, achieving a cordless device. We believe that this feature will enable a straightforward installation in all medical institutions.

To achieve a high detection rate with this magnetic method, surgeons need to receive extra training. Fortunately, the training process is comparable to the training process for the RI method, and surgeons that are experienced in performing SLNBs will generally perform well with this technique. In this study, the surgery was performed by experienced surgeons that perform 50 to 100 operations per year.

The improvement of this magnetic method was achieved by administering the radioactive colloids ( 99m Tc) and Resovist up to 24 hours before the surgery. As it is necessary to identify the location of the node from above the skin before the skin incision, a combination with a blue dye was used to improve detection during surgery. Further studies are planned to evaluate the capacity of Resovist to be retained in the lymph nodes for longer periods (>24 hours) to allow delayed sentinel node biopsy. A longer retention time of Resovist would be a clear advantage over the RI method, with a retention time limited by the half /uni2010 life of the Technetium and the blue dye which is rapidly absorbed.

The residual magnetic nanoparticles from Resovist in the breast do not permit the patient to undergo an MRI analysis. Further studies are needed to evaluate the exact duration the skin tattoo retains magnetic activity. However, we have performed an abdominal MRI on a patient 6 months after the SPIO injection without any problems.

In the present study, patients with liver or renal failure were excluded from the study. We did not observe any postoperative hepatic or renal toxicity due to Resovist; therefore, we will evaluate the inclusion of those patients in future studies.

Currently, we are conducting a clinical study to evaluate the possibility of reducing the current dose of Resovist by half (to 0.5 mL) to reduce the pigment deposition and residual iron in the breast as well as to increase the safety of this method.

## 5 | CONCLUSION

SLNB using the Resovist magnetic nanoparticles and a newly developed handheld probe can be considered as an equivalent method to the conventional RI method. This method does not use radioactive isotopes, and therefore it does not require a radiation /uni2010 controlled area and can be safely implemented without facility restrictions.
